answers.body_markdown:
I&#39;m not quite sure what you&#39;re asking, so sorry if I misinterpret you or if these answers have nothing to do with your question.

It&#39;s kind of a weird question.  It sounds like you want your computer system to maintain an input buffer for you that you can manipulate freely, but without explicitly declaring a variable within your program.  So I guess that means you could say things like

    read_input_into_buffer();

or

    if(buffer_contents_equal_to(&quot;exit&quot;)) {
        /* user typed &quot;exit&quot; */
        printf(&quot;Goodbye!\n&quot;);
        exit(0);
    }

But no, I don&#39;t know of a system that has calls like these.  And even if there were such a system, there isn&#39;t really that much difference in expressive power as compared to what you *can* do under most programming systems:

    char buffer[100];
    read_input_into(buffer, 100);

    if(string_equal_to(buffer, &quot;exit&quot;)) {
        printf(&quot;Goodbye!\n&quot;);
        exit(0);
    }

(That&#39;s obviously pseudocode.  In C, the actual function calls you&#39;d use might be `fgets` to read a line and `strcmp` to compare strings, although you&#39;d need to do some work around the edges, such as coping with the trailing newline that `fgets` helpfully leaves in the buffer for you.)

But yes, in this latter, more realistic case you *do* have to allocate a buffer variable in your code (which I guess is precisely what you don&#39;t want to do), and you do have to pick a size for that buffer, etc.

----

Another answer to your question concerns the character-at-a-time case.  Instead of writing

    int c;
    c = getchar();
    if(c == &#39;y&#39;) {
        /* user said yes */
        ...
    }

you could theoretically compress this down to

    if(getchar() == &#39;y&#39;) {
        /* user said yes */
        ...
    }

Here you&#39;ve achieved your goal of not storing the user&#39;s input in a variable, but it&#39;s a false economy, because just comparing against a single character is almost never what you really want to do.  For example, in this case, you probably want to let the user type either `y` or `Y`, and to do that, you need to go back to using the variable:

    c = getchar();
    if(c == &#39;y&#39; || c == &#39;Y&#39;) {
        /* user said yes */
        ...
    }

Or you might be looking for a number of different responses, in which case you&#39;re also going to need the variable:

    c = getchar();
    if(c == &#39;y&#39; || c == &#39;Y&#39;) {
        /* user said yes */
        ...
    } else if(c == &#39;n&#39; || c == &#39;N&#39;) {
        /* user said no */
        ...
    } else ...

----

One final answer:  Under Unix-like systems, it&#39;s possible to use the `mmap()` call to map an entire file into your address space.  (And I suspect Windows has something similar.)  This means you don&#39;t have to allocate any buffers to read the file into, or use calls like `read()` or `fread()` to read characters from the file into your buffer — instead, the whole contents of file are just *there*.  That sounds kind of like what you&#39;re trying to do, although it only works for files in the filesystem.  You couldn&#39;t use it for user input from stdin, which I guess is what you&#39;re asking about.

----

And one final, *final* answer: In comments, you&#39;ve said you&#39;re trying to read user input that might be an int or might be a float.  And it sounds like your problem is that, once you&#39;ve read it as (say) an int, there&#39;s no way to &quot;go back in time&quot; and read it as a float, instead.

If you&#39;ve been taught that the way to read an int is by calling `scanf(&quot;%d&quot;, &amp;i)`, and that the way to read a float is by calling `scanf(&quot;%f&quot;, &amp;f)`, then it&#39;s true, once you&#39;ve read the input one way, you&#39;re stuck.

But that&#39;s *not* the only way to read input.  There are lots of other (and better) ways, that give you more flexibility.  This is probably what you want, although I have to say, the *only* way(s) to achieve this flexibility is going to require, yes, reading the input into a temporary buffer first.  (I&#39;m still not sure what you mean when you say you want to avoid that somehow.)

Here&#39;s one straightforward example of reading an input in two different ways.  (I sincerely hope I have not just done your homework for you.)

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    #include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
    
    int main()
    {
        char line[100];
        int i;
        double d;
        char *endp;
    
        printf(&quot;Enter an integer or a floating-point number:\n&quot;);
        fgets(line, sizeof(line), stdin);
    
        i = strtol(line, &amp;endp, 10);
    
        if(*endp == &#39;.&#39; || *endp == &#39;e&#39; || *endp == &#39;E&#39;) {
            d = strtod(line, &amp;endp);
            printf(&quot;You entered an floating-point number: %g\n&quot;, d);
        } else {
            /* it must have been a plain int */
            printf(&quot;You entered an int: %d\n&quot;, i);
        }
    }

You may not have encountered the `strtol` and `strtod` functions yet.  They both have a significant feature: after scanning and converting the digits in the string you give them, they give you something back: a pointer to the first character in the string they *didn&#39;t* convert.

So if you convert the string `&quot;123&quot;`, which is all digits, either function is able to use up the whole string, so the &quot;end pointer&quot; they give you back points to the `\0` at the end of the string.  If you try to convert the string `&quot;456!&quot;`, either function will convert the `4`, `5`, and `6`, and give you back a pointer to the non-digit `!` character.  But if you try to convert the string `&quot;123.456&quot;`, the `strtol` function considers the `&#39;.&#39;` character to be a non-digit, and gives you back a pointer to that character.  `strtod`, on the other hand, is obviously perfectly happy to read both the `&#39;.&#39;` and the fractional digits after it.

If this was in fact your question, and if you had been under the impression that `scanf` was the only way to read user input, please see [this other question](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58403537/what-can-i-use-to-parse-input-instead-of-scanf).

&gt;  Is this right? If so, where in the java documentation does it say this?

Yes, that is right- the Java specs say this at [JLS 17.4.5. Happens-before Order][1]

---
In the example you gave, there is a race beetween the two threads. Also, in order for thread2 to have visibility about what thread1 did, thread2 should **read** `x` (the volatile variable) before reading `y`. If thread2 reads `y` only, which is not volatile, then visibility of the changed `y` value is not guaranteed.

---
You can modify the example code as below. There is still a race, so the output can be `x=0 y=0`, `x=0 y=1` or `x=1 y=1`. But using volatile assures that the program will never output `x=1 y=0`.

    public class UseVolatile {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Shared shared = new Shared();
            new Thread(() -&gt; shared.setOne()).start();
            new Thread(() -&gt; {
                int x = shared.getX();
                int y = shared.getY();
                System.out.printf(&quot;x=%d y=%d%n&quot;, x, y);
            }).start();
        }
    }
    class Shared {
        private int y = 0;
        private volatile int x = 0;
    
        public void setOne() {
            y = 1;
            x = 1;
        }
        public int getX() {
            return x;
        }
        public int getY() {
            return y;
        }
    }

---
**Edit**

We can work out why output `x=1 y=0` can&#39;t happen. Referring to the JLS: 

&gt; Two actions can be ordered by a happens-before relationship. If one action happens-before another, then the first is visible to and ordered before the second.

&gt; If we have two actions x and y, we write hb(x, y) to indicate that x happens-before y.

&gt; If x and y are actions of the same thread and x comes before y in program order, then hb(x, y). **(1)**

&gt; If hb(x, y) and hb(y, z), then hb(x, z). **(2)**

&gt; A write to a volatile field happens-before every subsequent read of that field. **(3)**

Actions happening in the same threads are ordered due to (1).
So the write to `y` happens-before the write to `x` in thread 1.

Write to volatile `x` in thread1, happens-before reading the updated value of `x` in thread2, due to (3).

And reading `x` happens-before reading `y` in thread2, due to (1).

Combining all of these, it follows that if thread2 sees the updated value for `x`, then the read of `y` in this thread will happen-before the write to `y`in the other thread (and visibility of the updated value is guaranteed).

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-17.html#jls-17.4.5

Let&#39;s look at your second example first.

    class Shared {
    
      private int y = 0;
      private volatile int x = 0;
    
      public void setOne() {
        y = 1; //(1)
        x = 1; //(2)
      }
    
      public int getXPlusY() {
        int local = x; //(3)
        return local + y; //(4)
      }
    }

We know that there is a *happens-before* relationship between (1) and (2) due to *program order*:

&gt; If x and y are actions of the same thread and x comes before y in program order, then hb(x, y).

Since `x` is volatile, we know that there&#39;s a *happens-before* relationship between (2) and (3)

&gt; A write to a volatile field (&#167;8.3.1.4) happens-before every subsequent read of that field.

And there is a *happens-before* relationship between (3) and (4) due to *program order* again:

&gt; If x and y are actions of the same thread and x comes before y in program order, then hb(x, y).

Therefore, we have a *happens-before* chain (1) → (2), (2) → (3), (3) → (4)

And since *happens-before* is a transitive relation (if A happens before B and B happens before C, then A happens before C) that means that **(1) has a *happens-before* relation with (4)**.

Now let&#39;s look at the first example:


    class Shared {
    
      private int y = 0;
      private volatile int x = 0;
    
      public void setOne() {
        y = 1; //(1)
        x = 1; //(2)
      }
    
      public int getY() {
        return y; //(3)
      }
    }

There&#39;s again a *happens-before* relation between (1) and (2), but that&#39;s about it. Since `x` is not read by the second thread, we have no *happens-before* between (2) and (3). Therefore we have **no *happens-before* relation between (1) and (3)**.

The quotes were taken from [Chapter 17 of the Java Language Specification (JLS)][1]


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-17.html

